05320nam a22011535i 9780228018650DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280186507 a10.1515/97802280186502doi  a(DE-B1597)658123  a(OCoLC)1375556050  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9199.4.A53bP76 2023 7aMUS0500002bisacsh04aC811/.542231 aAnderson, Matthew R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProphets of Love :bThe Unlikely Kinship of Leonard Cohen and the Apostle Paul /cMatthew R. Anderson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAdvancing Studies in Religion ;v1500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAlmost Like the Blues -- tLet Us Compare Mythologies -- tLonely Wooden Tower -- tDeath of a Ladies’ Man -- tTraveling Light -- tI’m Your Man -- tEverybody Knows -- tBirds on a Wire -- tThe Secret Chord -- tCome Healing -- tThanks for the Dance -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLeonard Cohen and the Apostle Paul might be imagined as brothers with wildly different characters but a strong family resemblance. Paul, the elder sibling, was awkward, abrasive, and zealous. Leonard, the successful younger brother, was a smooth-talking romantic, prone to addiction and depression. Paul died a martyr, not knowing his words would have any effect on the world. Leonard could see his canonization within his lifetime. Yet each became a prophet in his own time, and a poet for the ages.In Prophets of Love Matthew Anderson traces surprising connections between two Jewish thinkers separated by millennia. He explores Leonard's and Paul’s mysticism, their Judaism, their fascination with Jesus, their countercultural perspectives on sex, their ideas about love, and how they each embodied being men. Anderson considers their ambiguous relationships with women, on whom they depended and from whom they often profited, as well as how their legacies continue to evolve and be re-interpreted. This book emphasizes that Paul was first and foremost a Jew, and never rejected his Judaism. At the same time, it sheds new light on the biblical worldviews and language underlying and inspiring every line of Cohen’s poetry.Prophets of Love alters our views of both Leonard Cohen and the Apostle Paul, re-introducing us to two poetic prophets of divine and human love.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aMUSIC / Individual Composer & Musician.2bisacsh  a#MeToo.  aBaldy.  aBuddhism.  aCanada.  aCanadian literature.  aChristianity.  aEliezar.  aJesus.  aJew.  aJudaism.  aMontreal.  aPaul.  aPhilemon.  aRomans.  aRoshi.  aZen.  aancient.  aantisemitism.  aapocalypticism.  aapostle.  aasceticism.  abible.  abiblical studies.  acohen.  across.  adesire.  aepistolary.  afasting.  aforgiveness.  agender.  agrace.  aguilt.  aintersectionality.  akosher.  alonging.  alove.  amasculinity.  amuse.  amusic.  amysticism.  anew testament.  apassion.  apatriarchy.  apatristic.  apoetry.  arabbi.  areception.  arhetoric.  aromance.  asaint.  ascripture.  asex.  asynagogue.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228018650?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228018650423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228018650/or